        "title": "8. Missing entirely: `cli.py` and integration/E2E",
        "content": "\n- `cli.py`'s `main()` — argument parsing (`--config`, `--dry-run`) wiring to `run_sync` — zero coverage, trivial to add with `monkeypatch` on `pipeline.run_sync`.\n- No test exercises the full chain **fetch → filter → dedup → notify** together with realistic fixture payloads for at least one ATS (e.g. record a real Greenhouse response shape as a JSON fixture, run it through `parse_greenhouse` → `filter_jobs` → `Store.diff` → assert the notifier sees the right job). This is the integration-test gap: unit tests on each stage don't catch a contract mismatch between stages (e.g. `filter_jobs` expecting a field `parse_greenhouse` doesn't set).\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "Summary — priority order to close gaps",
        "content": "1. **`models.py` + `filters.py`** — pure, fast, highest logic-bug risk, cheapest to write.\n2. **`store.py`** — dedup correctness is the core value prop of the tool; in-memory SQLite makes this cheap.\n3. **`fetchers.py` parsers** — largest count of untested functions and the most likely to silently break on vendor changes; even a thin \"happy path + empty payload\" test per parser catches most regressions.\n4. **`notify.py` `dispatch` isolation** — one-line-of-value test (`boom`/`ok` pattern above) that guards an important resilience property.\n5. **`agent.py` CLI helpers** — `_normalize_ats` and `cmd_db_new`'s truncation/posted-days logic are the two riskiest pieces of hand-rolled logic in the file.\n6. **`pipeline.py` / `cli.py`** — thin orchestration; cover last, mostly for wiring regressions.",
